{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16085"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16085"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.07,0.13,0.1,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63852"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8776"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49282"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8592"},{"type":"tags","id":"8595"},{"type":"tags","id":"10615"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20961"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63852"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the precursor cell type that forms syncytiotrophoblasts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypoblast cells","Primitive endoderm cells","Epiblast cells","Inner cell mass cells","Cytotrophoblasts"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the outer layer of the blastocyst (trophectoderm) gives rise to the trophoblast lineage. \u003Cstrong\u003ECytotrophoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are the precursor cells that fuse together to form multinucleated syncytiotrophoblasts, which are essential for implantation and placental development. These syncytiotrophoblasts produce hormones like human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) and facilitate maternal-fetal exchange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einner cell mass cells\u003C/strong\u003E give rise to the embryo proper and do not contribute to trophoblast formation. They differentiate into the epiblast and hypoblast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiblast cells\u003C/strong\u003E form the three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm) of the developing embryo through gastrulation. They are not involved in trophoblast development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoblast cells\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimitive endoderm cells\u003C/strong\u003E are the same structure (primitive endoderm is the formal name, hypoblast is the traditional term). These cells form the yolk sac and do not contribute to trophoblast formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding trophoblast development is clinically relevant as abnormalities in this process can lead to various pregnancy complications, including pre-eclampsia and gestational trophoblastic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cytotrophoblasts are the precursor cells that fuse to form syncytiotrophoblasts during placental development.","Syncytiotrophoblasts are essential for hormone production and maternal-fetal exchange in pregnancy.","The trophoblast lineage differentiates from the trophectoderm of the blastocyst during early embryonic development."],"references":["Roberts RM, Ezashi T, Schulz LC, Sugimoto J, Schust DJ, Khan T, Zhou J. Syncytins expressed in human placental trophoblast. Placenta. 2021 Sep 15;113:8-14. doi: 10.1016/j.placenta.2021.01.006. Epub 2021 Jan 15. PMID: 33504453; PMCID: PMC8280254.","Wang Y, Zhao S. Vascular Biology of the Placenta. San Rafael (CA): Morgan \u0026 Claypool Life Sciences; 2010. Chapter 4, Cell Types of the Placenta. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK53245/","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49282"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16085"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49282"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T18:26:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T18:27:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8776"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63852"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retri